    {
      "id": "emfo",
      "code_hash": "a53153ff3779475f23f75a77766efd22",
      "outputs": [
        {
          "type": "data",
          "data": {
            "text/markdown": "<span class=\"markdown prose dark:prose-invert contents\"><h2 id=\"section-2-from-grid-to-token-the-bridge\">Section 2 \u2014 From Grid to Token: The Bridge</h2>\n<span class=\"paragraph\">The NCA grid looks nothing like language. A 16x16 grid of coloured\nsquares, evolving step by step under a hidden rule.</span>\n<span class=\"paragraph\">But to train a transformer on it, we need <strong>tokens</strong> \u2014 integers from\na fixed vocabulary. This section walks through the tokenisation pipeline\nand reveals the surprise: NCA token frequencies follow the same\npower-law distribution as natural language.</span></span>"
          }
        }
      ],
      "console": []
    },
    {
      "id": "TqIu",
      "code_hash": "4cf75b8e968fc0517d17582f352f04d1",
      "outputs": [
        {
          "type": "data",
          "data": {
            "text/markdown": "<span class=\"markdown prose dark:prose-invert contents\"><h2 id=\"section-3-the-finding-what-did-nca-pre-training-actually-install\">Section 3 - The Finding: What Did NCA Pre-Training Actually Install?</h2>\n<span class=\"paragraph\">We train two tiny transformers:</span>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Scratch:</strong> random initialisation, no pre-training</li>\n<li><strong>NCA:</strong> pre-trained on NCA sequences, then switched to bracket task</li>\n</ul>\n<span class=\"paragraph\">Before either model sees a single bracket, we ask:\n<em>where does each model attend when shown a bracket sequence?</em></span></span>"
          }
        }
      ],
      "console": []
    },
    {
      "id": "AjVT",
      "code_hash": "81d6a28320ae0c1c12adb03814d6a9d1",
      "outputs": [
        {
          "type": "data",
          "data": {
            "text/markdown": "<span class=\"markdown prose dark:prose-invert contents\"><h2 id=\"section-4-the-problem-catastrophic-forgetting\">Section 4 - The Problem: Catastrophic Forgetting</h2>\n<span class=\"paragraph\">Standard fine-tuning <strong>destroys</strong> the pre-trained circuits.\nThis is <strong>catastrophic forgetting</strong> visible at the circuit level\nfor the first time in NCA pre-training research.</span></span>"
          }
        }
      ],
      "console": []
    },
    {
      "id": "yCnT",
      "code_hash": "43882294de22a94a798f4b89da21c65b",
      "outputs": [
        {
          "type": "data",
          "data": {
            "text/markdown": "<span class=\"markdown prose dark:prose-invert contents\"><h2 id=\"section-5-the-fix-protecting-pre-trained-circuits\">Section 5 - The Fix: Protecting Pre-trained Circuits</h2>\n<span class=\"paragraph\">Two strategies, both validated across 3 seeds:</span>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Slow LR</strong> - 10x lower learning rate on transferred layers</li>\n<li><strong>Frozen attention</strong> - freeze attention weights, only train MLPs</li>\n</ul>\n<span class=\"paragraph\">Both preserve &gt;90% of the Layer 1 structure through 80 epochs.</span></span>"
          }
        }
      ],
      "console": []
    },
    {
      "id": "lgWD",
      "code_hash": "7c3b18d3b910784ef1ba740c08169c1d",
      "outputs": [
        {
          "type": "data",
          "data": {
            "text/markdown": "<span class=\"markdown prose dark:prose-invert contents\"><h2 id=\"section-6-where-this-leads-petri-dish-nca\">Section 6 - Where This Leads: Petri Dish NCA</h2>\n<span class=\"paragraph\">What if the NCA itself never stopped learning?</span>\n<span class=\"paragraph\"><strong>Petri Dish Neural Cellular Automata</strong> (Sakana AI, ALIFE 2025):\nmultiple NCA agents compete for territory on a shared grid,\neach continuously updating their own parameters via backpropagation\nduring the simulation itself.</span></span>"
          }
        }
      ],
      "console": []
    },
